title: For Sale:  *** SOLD *** BIANCHI X15 LG - Vintage Collectable
postcontent:
During the late sixties and early seventies, in response to "civilian advisors" needing to comfortably carry larger handguns, John Bianchi developed the revolutionary Model X15 Shoulder Holster, one of the most copied shoulder holster designs of all time.  

This very early vintage Bianchi X15 with "PATENT PEND" embossing is a timeless piece of American handgun holster history from one of the premier holster designers of our time. That it is still in production and supported by Bianchi today is a true testament to John's original and innovative design.  

After years of service for both Smiths and Colts, this Vietnam era example was retired to a climate-controlled environment for the last 35 years. It is in very good to excellent condition with near perfect stitching, retainer strap (replaced by Bianchi) and original supple leather shoulder strap and harness.

Sturdy and rigid at the holster cradle and supple and soft at the shoulder, this prime example requires no break in and is perfect for the collector or a discriminating individual who appreciates the value of owning a high quality, true vintage holster of historical significance.  
Price: $50-plus s/h.

title: For Sale:  Rare Special Colt SAA - .45 - 4 Â¾ â Barrel
postcontent:
Quite rare Colt SAA,  C & R eligible.

FIRST OF ALL, I am not a Colt SAA expert. I know just enough to research Colt books and get confused.

Over a collecting lifetime, have acquired several pistols as âcommonâ, which later turned out
to have serious collector interest. Dumb luck.

This SAA may fit into this category.

A serious SAA collector may determine this to be a Colt âerrorâ and make a serious offer.
Alternately, a serious collector may determine this SAA to not be an error. In that case
will grab a box of GOEX black powder ammunition and head for the range.

For starters: Colt SAA, serial number 347XXX, .45, 4 Â¾â barrel, about 25% blue mostly around
extractor housing, matching serial number on frame and right side of back strap and trigger guard strap.
Last 2 digits on cylinder face. âFâ in hammer slot. Trigger guard proof mark and inspector 3.
There are a small number of pockmarks visible. It has aftermarket stag grips.

There is a Colt Archive letter saying serial # 347XXX, .45/c, 4 Â¾â, Blue, was shipped to St. Louis in 1925.

Of interest, the 4 Â¾â barrel has a single line barrel address.
Also, the barrel address has the Broken âOâ in âHartfordâ.

Referencing Keith Cochranâs COLT PEACEMAKER ENCYCLOPEDIA, Errors Pg 144-145.
Also page 17, Barrel Address Lettering, âThese errors are very rare.â

Now the conflicts. The encyclopedia, page 75, identifies the barrelâs caliber marking being used 1929 â 1940.
The Broken âOâ is identified as occurring about 1926 â 1936.

Final consideration, an ampersand is stamped on right rear trigger guard indicating a visit back to the factory,
Colt Archives does not maintain records of repairs. It is common knowledge that Colt never threw out anything usable.
Did Colt put a mis-stamped barrel on this SAA during a factory visit ?

This is as far as I can take it. If anyone can offer positive information or questions,
please email me. I do not live on the computer, but will get back to you as soon as possible.

I am a private collector, slowly liquidating a personal collection. Old age and that sort of stuff.
